WCAG Success Criteria for Motion

03

Before we dive further into implementation suggestions, let's discuss how motion comes up in the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines.

WCAG provides actionable information for creating better websites and mobile applications.

Remember the levels for success criteria in WCAG:

  • Level A is considered the least strict. These success criteria are absolutely essential for every website.
  • Level AA is for websites can be considered reasonably accessible, and should be considered the minimum baseline.
  • Level AAA is considered optimally accessible.

Here are some motion-related guidelines from WCAG 2.2:

  • 2.2.2 Pause, Stop, Hide - Level A. "Moving, blinking, and scrolling" refers to content in which the visible content conveys a sense of motion. This one is huge for people with ADHD and other conditions that make moving websites hell to navigate and use. You must provide mechanisms to make the motion stop. Tapping into prefers-reduced-motion to keep motion and autoplaying video from occurring in the first place would be a top technique!
  • 2.3.1 Three Flashes or Below Threshold - Level A. Web pages do not contain anything that flashes more than three times in any one-second period, or the flash is below the general flash and red flash thresholds. This one gets quite specific about luminance values in flashing content and the amount of screen real estate it takes up. There is also a Level AAA criterion with no threshold.
  • 2.3.3 Animation from Interactions - Level AAA. Motion animation triggered by interaction can be disabled unless the animation is essential to the functionality or the information being conveyed. While a Level AAA criterion, this one typically isn’t complicated to meet by making transitions and animations respond to reduced-motion settings. So why not do it?
